I think I spent roughly as much time getting git authentication to work as I did implementing the actual task; somewhat annoying that the permissions are not set up to work with GitHub SSO over https, so convenience IDE integration of git not working properly.

Other than that, nice project, gave me the opportunity to try out something I haven't had much experience with before (criteria queries) after thinking for a bit about what would make sense in terms of separation of concerns, and learn some new things about this.

Overall, I could have spent more time on cleaning up the mvc tests for search, since they were more or less redundant after separating business logic out from controller layer, but decided to remove them instead over re-writing all the mock test cases due to time constraints.

I believe this to be motivated due to the fact that in this case, the tests vere very generic / low quality (testing business logic only through number of returned results, mixing with controller status tests, etc.), and in effect added more or less only false confidence to the test suite.

I would consider adding mvc tests again provided there was custom exception handling, input validation, etc. to be tested. Work to add exception handling and input validation could also have been part of this extension, but as the scope was more or less well defined, this was skipped. I could probably also have improved the criteria queries by further refinement as well, but overall I believe they are easy to understand in their current form.

Finally, I think this is a great topic to study, I have observed a significant overhead at work due to AI-generated code subtly not working as expected in maintenance scenarios, and developers spending much more time reviewing AI-generated PRs than I human-made ones lately (especially for code written in languages where there is not a lot of documentation available online, such as, e.g. RPG). It would be nice if this study can shed some light on whether this is just my subjective experience, or a systematic issue with over-reliance/over-trust when it comes to AI-assisted development.

    1 hour of "research" on the development stack - this included tasks like: (1) searching the internet for formal language documentation, such as Java technical documentation and the Spring framework documentation, (2) searching for context specific questions on sites like StackOverflow and other sites that Google search returned.

    .5 hour of 'break time'
